06588nmm a2200673Ia 9781771990349DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9781771990349  a(DE-B1597)665447  a(OCoLC)1048158305  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHM728b.S64 2015eb 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a305.5/5222300aSpeaking Power to Truth :bDigital Discourse and the Public Intellectual /ced. by Richard Hawkins, Michael Keren. 1aEdmonton, Alberta : bAthabasca University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b1 figure, 2 b&w maps, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Dialectics00tFrontmatter -- tPart I Perspectives -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: New Challenges to Knowledge in the Public Sphere -- tPart I Perspectives -- t1 Establishing the Public Legitimacy and Value of Scientific Knowledge in an Information Ether -- t2 Public Intellectuals, Media Intellectuals, and Academic Intellectuals: Comparing the Space of Opinion in Canada and the United States -- t3 The Eye of the Swarm: Collective Intelligence and the Public Intellectual -- t4 Creating the Conditions for an Intellectually Active People: What Today’s Public Intellectual Can Learn from Anonymous -- tPart II Case Studies -- t5 “Trust Me—I’m a Public Intellectual” Margaret Atwood’s and David Suzuki’s Social Epistemologies of Climate Science -- t6 Engendering a New Generation of Public Intellectuals: Speaking Truth to Power with Grace and Humility -- t7 Reflections on My Dubious Experience as a Public Intellectual -- t8 Intellectual Discourse Online -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnline discourse has created a new media environment for contributions to public life, one that challenges the social significance of the role of public intellectuals—intellectuals who, whether by choice or by circumstance, offer commentary on issues of the day. The value of such commentary is rooted in the assumption that, by virtue of their training and experience, intellectuals possess knowledge—that they understand what constitutes knowledge with respect to a particular topic, are able to distinguish it from mere opinion, and are in a position to define its relevance in different contexts. When intellectuals comment on matters of public concern, they are accordingly presumed to speak truth, whether they are writing books or op-ed columns or appearing as guests on radio and television news programs. At the same time, with increasing frequency, discourse on public life is taking place online. This new digital environment is characterized by abundance—an abundance of speakers, discussion, and access. But has this abundance of discourse—this democratization of knowledge, as some describe it—brought with it a corresponding increase in truth?Casting doubt on the assertion that online discourse, with its proliferation of voices, will somehow yield collective wisdom, Speaking Power to Truth raises concerns that this wealth of digitally enabled commentary is, in fact, too often bereft of the hallmarks of intellectual discourse: an epistemological framework and the provision of evidence to substantiate claims. Instead, the pursuit of truth finds itself in competition with the quest for public reputation, access to influence, and enhanced visibility. But as knowledge is drawn into the orbit of power, and as the line between knowledge and opinion is blurred, what role will the public intellectual play in the promotion and nurturing of democratic processes and goals? In exploring the implications of the digital transition, the contributors to Speaking Power to Truth provide both empirical evidence of, and philosophical reflection on, the current and future role of the public intellectual in a technologically mediated public sphere. With contributions by Karim-Aly Kassam, Barrry Cooper, Jacob G. Foster, Richard Hawkins, Michael Keren, Boaz Miller, Liz Pirnie, and Eleanor Townsley.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunicationxSocial aspects. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aIntellectual life. 0aIntellectualsvCase studies. 0aIntellectuals. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aclimate change, media studies, journalism, internet, journalists, social values, climate science, social policy.1 aCooper, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Jacob G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKassam, Karim-Aly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeren, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeren, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Boaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPirnie, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTownsley, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771990349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771990349/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles